              margin-top: 2px !important;">Grab mulls takeover of Rival GoTo at $7 billion valuation</h2>
        </mj-text> 
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/grab-goto-merger.png" alt="Grab Holdings GoTo Group Merger" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">Picture of Grab and GoTo delivery personnel. Credits: Yuki Kohara
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Singapore-based Grab Holdings and Indonesia’s GoTo Group have <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-05-02-2025-accelerated-talks" target="_blank">accelerated talks</a> for a potential merger. The transaction being discussed could value GoTo at $7 billion. GoTo’s stock jumped 6.2% on the news, whereas Grab’s shares experienced a decline of 4%. If the deal goes through, it would create a regional giant with over 650 million consumers.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The market has been highly competitive, with both firms posting persistent losses. However, the merger would allow the company to cut costs and consolidate market share. The potential merger would face some issues, including regulatory scrutiny and antitrust concerns.</p>
        </mj-text>
