              margin-top: 2px !important;">No more new unicorns?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/unicorn-valuation-all-time-highs.jpg" alt="Unicorn Count and Money Valuation" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>The number of new unicorns (red bars) has dropped significantly since 2022</strong>, indicating a slowdown in startup funding and fewer companies crossing the $1 billion valuation mark. According to the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-05-02-2025-2024-gser" target="_blank">2024 Global Startup Ecosystems Report (GSER)</a>, 2023 saw <strong>58 percent fewer new unicorns</strong> than 2022 and 87 percent fewer than the unicorn peak of 2021.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Market corrections</strong> – The post-money valuation growth (light blue background) peaked in 2021, suggesting inflated valuations during the boom period. The correction afterward has likely led to some unicorns losing their status.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>High interest rates and tighter funding</strong>—Since 2022, higher interest rates and tighter venture capital (VC) funding have made it harder for startups to raise large rounds, limiting expansion and decreasing investor appetite.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Increased exits or failures</strong> – Some unicorns IPO’d, got acquired, or shut down, reducing the number of active unicorns despite fewer new ones entering the pool. As of September 2024, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-05-02-2025-475-companies-had-exited" target="_blank">475 companies had exited</a> the market.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Economic uncertainty</strong> – Global economic instability, cautious investor sentiment, and sector-specific downturns (e.g., tech layoffs and lower SaaS multiples) have made it harder for startups to achieve or maintain unicorn status.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
