            <strong>🇿🇦 De Beers struggling against declining diamond demand</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          De Beers is grappling with <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-05-02-2025-plummeting-demand" target="_blank">plummeting demand</a> and angry buyers as it grapples with one of the worst downturns in its history. De Beers’ parent company, Anglo American Plc, is trying to exit the diamond business but is struggling to find a buyer willing to pay a premium.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          De Beers was once a near-monopoly in the 20th century, controlling about 90% of the diamond market. However, US antitrust rulings and the rise of lab-grown diamonds have posed challenges for the company. Diamond demand has dropped by 50% since 2019 as China’s economic slowdown compounds trouble.
          </p>
